 6. Does anybody know the history of Camper Van Beethoven?

    The history of this band is unclear, but we have been able to
    piece together some events in their history from what remains of
    their writings. This partial history was found in the liner notes
    of their albums:

     At some time around 1981, some of the people who were
     eventually to form Camper Van Beethoven, including Chris
     Molla and David Lowery, were in a Santa Cruz band called Box
     O' Laffs, who released exactly one album entitled
     _Dogbook_, cassette only on the now-defunct label Warpt
     Records West.  At various times Campers David Lowery, Chriss
     Molla, Chris Pedersen, Anthony Guess and Richie West were
     all members of Box O' Laffs.

     In 1982 David Lowery, Chris Molla, Bill ``Where the Hell
     is'' McDonald, and Cracker guitarist John Hickman were
     members of The Estonian Gauchos, a band which pretty much
     mutated into Camper Van Beethoven.

     Formed in 1983 in Redlands, California, Camper Van Beethoven
     survived its first summer playing folk versions of hardcore
     classics and Russian folks songs to somewhat mystified
     hardcore audiences.  In 1984 the band moved to Santa Cruz . . .
     In June 1985 they released their first album . . .

    A few other facts are known:

    In 1987 the Monks of Doom made their first record. The Monks of
    Doom are Greg Lisher, Chris Pedersen, and Victor Krummenacher from
    Camper Van Beethoven, and David Immergluck from The Ophelias. In
    the same year Chris Molla left Camper Van Beethoven.

    In 1988 Jonathan Segel was kicked out of Camper Van Beethoven
    while on vacation in southeast Asia immediately following the
    recording of _Storytelling_. Essentially Lowery's decision.

    In 1989, before the recording of _Key Lime Pie_, Jonathan Segel
    left Camper Van Beethoven. He was replaced by Morgan Fichter,
    originally from Harm Farm.

    In 1990, during their European Tour, the Campers dissolved for
    good.

    In 1992, Cracker released their first album.

    In 1993, the Monks of Doom began an extended hiatus.

    In an interview from the Jan/Feb '87 issue of _The Bob_, David
    Lowery said:

     I've been in a lot of different bands in Southern California
     with Chris Molla, and Victor (Krummenacher) was from that
     same scene down there.  One summer about three-and-a-half
     years ago a bunch of us got together and decided to do stuff
     that would irritate people that come to the kind of parties
     where we saw live music, which was mostly hardcore at the
     time.  So we were being really acoustic, and we had this
     violin player named Daniel Blume who was really into the
     idea.  It was a lot of fun.  It was just really garagey,
     trashy, acoustic music, and it was really fun.  We had a
     good time with it.

